<h2>1. Choose the right communication channel</h2>
<h3>Essential</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Use the NHS App to send non-urgent messages securely at no cost.</li>
    <li>Send messages in a format that people with a recorded communication need can access.</a>
    </li>
  </ul>
<h3>Best practice</h3>
<ul>
  <li>If you need to send an SMS, make sure you use as few message fragments as possible to reduce costs. </li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/content/messaging-patients/communication-channels-for-messages">Find out more about different communication channels for messages</a>.</p>
<h2>2. Ensure messages are accessible and inclusive</h2>
<h3>Essential</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Use the NHS Content guide to write in short sentences and plain English and use inclusive language.</li>
  <li>Make your messages available in alternative formats (also known as accessible formats).</a>
  </li>
  <li>Make sure you're familiar with the NHS Accessible Information Standard.</a>
  </li>
</ul>
<h3>Best practice</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Make all possible efforts to translate your messages into other languages.</a>
  </li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/content/messaging-patients/send-accessible-messages">Find out more about sending accessible and inclusive messages</a>.</p>
<h2>3. Send messages that patients can trust</h2>
<h3>Essential</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Do not use a third-party link shortening service to reduce the length of links.</li>
  <li>Use an appropriate SenderID (the text that appears instead of a telephone number).</li>
  <li>Take steps to protect people from spam or phishing.</a>
  </li>
</ul>
<h3>Best practice</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Use the NHS Content guide when creating new messages so they have a consistent style.</li>
  <li>Always ask someone else to check your messages for errors before you send them.</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/content/messaging-patients/send-messages-that-patients-trust">Find out more about sending messages that patients trust</a>.</p>
<h2>4. Ensure messages are appropriate and relevant to the recipient</h2>
<h3>Essential</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Use the information you have available to identify specific groups of people.</li>
  <li>Tailor message content so it's relevant to those specific groups.</li>
  <li>Do not include confidential information, as other people could see messages.</li>
  <li>Make sure your messages follow UK GDPR and data protection legislation.</a>
  </li>
</ul>
<h3>Best practice</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Use voice and tone guidance to write messages that make patients feel cared for.</li>
  <li>Share general information by putting a banner on your website or a post on social media.</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="/content/messaging-patients/send-messages-that-are-appropriate-and-relevant">Find out more about sending personalised, appropriate and relevant messages</a>.</p>
